ey + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" + _userTablePasswordField + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" from \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" + _userTable + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" where \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" + _userTableUserField + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" = ?\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\";\\\\\\\\n        _roleSql = \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"select r.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" + _roleTableRoleField\\\\\\\\n                   + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" from \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n                   + _roleTable\\\\\\\\n                   + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" r, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n                   + _userRoleTable\\\\\\\\n                   + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" u where u.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n                   + _userRoleTableUserKey\\\\\\\\n                   + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" = ?\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n                   + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and r.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n                   + _roleTableKey\\\\\\\\n                   + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" = u.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n                   + _userRoleTableRoleKey;\\\\\\\\n        \\\\\\\\n        Loader.loadClass(this.getClass(), _jdbcDriver).newInstance();\\\\\\\\n        super.doStart();\\\\\\\\n    }\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n    /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */\\\\\\\\n    public String getConfig()\\\\\\\\n    {\\\\\\\\n        return _config;\\\\\\\\n    }\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n    /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */\\\\\\\\n    /**\\\\\\\\n     * Load JDBC connection configuration from properties file.\\\\\\\\n     * \\\\\\\\n     * @param config Filename or url of user properties file.\\\\\\\\n     */\\\\\\\\n    public void setConfig(String config)\\\\\\\\n    {        \\\\\\\\n        if (isRunning())\\\\\\\\n            throw new IllegalStateException(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Running\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\");\\\\\\\\n        _config=config;\\\\\\\\n    }\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n    /* ------------------------------------------------------------ */\\\\\\\\n    /**\\\\\\\\n     * (re)Connect to database with parameters setup by loadConfig()\\\\\\\\n     */\\\\\\\\n    public void connectDatabase()\\\\\\\\n    {\\\\\\\\n        try\\\\\\\\n        {\\\\\\\\n            Class.forName(_jdbcDriver);\\\\\\\\n            _con = DriverManager.getConnection(_url, _userName, _password);\\\\\\\\n        }\\\\\\\\n        catch (SQLException e)\\\\\\\\n        {\\\\\\\\n            LOG.warn(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"UserRealm \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" + getName() + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" could not connect to database; will try later\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", e);\\\\\\\\n        }\\\\\\\\n        catch (ClassNotFoundException e)\\\\\\\\n        {\\\\\\\\n            LOG.warn(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"UserRealm \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" + getName() + \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" could not connect to database; will try later\\\\\\\\4T03-07-14-815397Z.log:16057:[thinking] I’m considering what happens if the pipe gets full after a timeout. In that case, blocking in write could lead to issues if I try to close it while writing. It seems closing `PipedInputStream` before the terminal is essential, so I should reverse the close order: close the terminal first, then close `nanoInput` and `nanoWriter`. Also, I’m curious whether repeated `ctrl-x` commands might cause issues since they could queue up if the terminal isn't ready. It’s all a bit complicated!\\\\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.jline:jline-reader:4.0.0/fix-javac-fail/pi-generation-2026-05-04T03-07-14-815397Z.log:16063:[recv] {\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"message_end\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"message\\\\\\\": {\\\\\\\"role\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"assistant\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"content\\\\\\\": [{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"thinking\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"thinking\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"**Evaluating exception handling**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm reflecting on catching exceptions and how ignoring them can violate best practices. It seems acceptable to catch `Exception`, but maybe it's not recommended by checkstyle. I should look into `IOException` and `InterruptedException` together. Also, I wonder about potential issues with too many `ctrl-x` commands in Nano and how that interacts with terminal input. There could be complications with thread handling, especially if attempts to join occur while edits are underway. It's all a bit tricky!\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Considering exception handling and streams**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm weighing the benefits of using `finally` in a `try` block, especially to ensure that if an edit throws an exception, I can still close resources robustly. There might be concerns about style guidelines against empty catches. It looks like I need to check if I should run the build since the user said it failed, but I can't inspect the compile. I also wonder if writing to `PipedOutputStream` before reading from `PipedInputStream` on the same thread would cause any issues. It's all quite intricate!\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Thinking through pipe management**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI’m considering what happens if the pipe gets full after a timeout. In that case, blocking in write could lead to issues if I try to close it while writing. It seems closing `PipedInputStream` before the terminal is essential, so I should reverse the close order: close the terminal first, then close `nanoInput` and `nanoWriter`. Also, I’m curious whether repeated `ctrl-x` commands might cause issues since they could queue up if the terminal isn't ready. It’s all a bit complicated!\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"thinkingSignature\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"rs_0b16fe48a743cbe90169f80d8c3b348197800fd28690e88b07\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"reasoning\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"encrypted_content\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"gAAAAABp-A2WfzCvcDj713F-a0Vwr5EDpOE5d-_SqDATpVS8oig2kSF8wClhtz4ryXM7_ik7sR-C_qVmQQ79UFVKVFUjdSv9L7HPdD8fY05RNKYVVAtxQ3mdHSh6_j6Zee7gm-QGiWIdvg_-vaHO1TI1OAae5ldq1LeWwP10ZD15BTIl-5qZzBMQbqNIVMqM1CeE4uoKuwON_wpYK8sFX1IAdnYapc-wbzl5BU4twV05FbqmywbRMNwrbmFg4couL1XLdP8fBtrtadcPNVp3DtsmpRIhpaOkuDcxpgnULdVMUIBVv6S-IdHnFCG9Fza3JQ8n8ClpEZRfOqm6eNqStZvq5Gu0g8d-nUaAwNMxVOBJGBo2